From: jcs@zoo.bt.co.uk (John C Sager)
Subject: Re: Bogomip
Date: Thu, 4 Nov 93 16:00:17 GMT

In article <CFxL04.8yH@eecs.nwu.edu>, hpa@ahab.eecs.nwu.edu (H. Peter Anvin N9ITP) writes:
> In article <1993Oct28.214204.173@gulasch.hanse.de> of comp.os.linux.misc,
>   elmar@gulasch.hanse.de (Elmar Folba) writes:
> > 
> > But there is another one - all else being equal, do you always get the same
> > BogoMips rating when you boot your system 10, 20, 30 times? ALWAYS?
> > 
> 
> I have found (on three different system) that the BogoMips rating is
> within about a 0.03 range.  That means 5% accuracy on the slowest
> system and 0.1% on the fastest one... pretty consistent IMHO.

I get very slight variations, which I put down to temperature effects.

BogoMips aren't the whole story. I have put Linux on a 486DX/33 with
8Mb ram, 8Mb swap on a 120Mb IDE drive with a cacheing disk controller.
The Bogomip rating is about 16.3. The kernel (pl13) compiles & builds
to zImage in 15 1/2 mins (having done the config, depend, clean already).

I also have put it up on a 386DX/25 system with 4Mb ram, 28Mb swap
on 2 MFM drives (40Mb & 120Mb). The Bogomip rating is 4.53 & the kernel
takes 1 1/2 hours to build. The Bogomip ratio is < 4 but the kernel
compile time ratio is about 6. I suspect the latter is nearer the true
difference in performance in general use. I expect the larger RAM &
the cacheing disk controller on the 486 have a lot of influence on
the numbers.

