From: imp@boulder.parcplace.com (Warner Losh)
Subject: Re: Gateway 2000 Pentium
Date: Wed, 3 Nov 1993 22:09:04 GMT

In article <1.14508.2381.0N27A0ED@satalink.com> john.will@satalink.com (John Will) writes:
>DR> I strongly reccomend AGAINST using a 14" or 15" monitor for 1024x768
>DR> or greater resolutions... not only is everything too small, it is VERY
>DR> bad on your eyes!  You wind up having to move closer to the monitor and
>DR> thusly get radiated, and having to focus closer in isn't fun either.
>
>I run 1024x768 on a 15" monitor, no sweat.  One of the nice things about
>X is I can size things to be easy to read at any resolution.  Now, if we're
>talking about Microsoft Windows, I can agree...

I run 1024x768 on my Hitachi 15" monitor at home all the time.  I have
a good refresh rate (about 69Hz).  I also run 1152x910 from time to
time, when I need a screen that size.  It is OK, having a poorer
refresh rate (about 59Hz) it causes more strain on the eyes.

At work I use 1152x910 all the time on a 17" monitor w/o any ill
effects.  The monitor has a Sony Trinitron tube and is connected to a
SS2.

