Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
From: spj@ukelele.gcr.com (Guru Aleph_Null)
Subject: Re: Hurd status and call for volunteers
Date: Thu, 4 Nov 1993 18:27:01 GMT

In article <1993Nov2.194952.14306@super.org> becker@super.org (Donald J. Becker) writes:
>In article <2b5jj7$rh@plootu.helsinki.fi>,
>
>"Don't dream it, be it."
>
>I'm big fan of the GNU project, and have worked on and with various pieces of
>GNU software since about 1986.  But this this is a little overboard.  I've
>been hearing about Hurd for years, and the story has always been that the
>design was pretty much complete, the implementation was nearly debugged, and
>"outside" suggestions and help wasn't welcome.

I don't think that was ever really true.  

>This seemed to be confirmed when the "official" GNU people weren't interested
>in Linux.  I heard statements that Hurd was going to be so much better that it
>wasn't worth working on Linux.

I don't think they were interested in Linux because Linux was
originally designed for only the i386/i486 machines.  I think that the
mission statement for the FSF was clearly to create a freed operating
system that will be portable to many machines.

>Luckily I only listened for a while.  Eventually I thought for myself and
>decided to give up the narrow-minded view that the officially-sanctioned Hurd
>would be _the_ Free OS.  Linux is reliable, complete, fast and innovative.
>Yes, you read that: innovative.  The innovation might not be obvious at first
>because Linux doesn't start by throwing away traditional interfaces just for
>the sake of doing things differently.  Instead it conforms to open, de-facto
>standards wherever it makes sense. 

Linux pretty much is _the_ Free OS (I don't really mean to snub
FreeBSD, but when you start seeing lots of people cutting CD-ROMs of
something, you throw some sacks of sand on the scales in favor of what
they're cutting...) for i386 machines. But what about 5 years from
now? Those 386/486/Pentium machines will still be around, but there
will be the Alphas, MIPS, and PowerPC machines to play with also.

>To echo the converse of earlier Hurd vs. Linux conversations: let's put the
>Hurd work over in the corner with the Lisp Machines.

Hurd's got a different goal: to be portable between architectures. How
many Linux ports have there been to machines other than 386/486's?
How many people use them? Hurd has its place, on the PowerPC 620 that
I plan on buying when it comes out. I don't know that Linux will ever
be ported to a lot of different architectures, and Linux certainly
won't be able to take advantage of multiprocessor architectures as
easily as Mach/Hurd will. Linux has its place: on i386/i486/Pentium
machines sitting in the corner 5 years from now.

>-- 
>
>Donald Becker                                         becker@super.org
>IDA Supercomputing Research Center
>17100 Science Drive, Bowie MD 20715                       301-805-7482


