Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
From: paulf@Csli.Stanford.EDU (Paul Flaherty)
Subject: Re: Hurd status and call for volunteers
Date: Thu, 4 Nov 1993 18:26:34 GMT

hallu@info.polymtl.ca (Louis-D. Dubeau) writes:

>I know Hurd isn't just a name. It's good to be innovative but you don't
>have to bring all the innovations at once. You can start from a
>single-server and divide the functionnality between several servers later.
>In the process you can also add new functionnality. You wouldn't have
>started from scratch if you had ported Linux or some other free OS to Mach
>and started from there instead of what you did.

There are at least two problems with this approach.  First of all, if you're
going to put in a major effort to produce an operating system, why not
create an integrated step forwards instead of hacks on an existing product?
Most of us have had experiences with that Bride of Frankenstein known as
"System V with BSD extensions", and would like to avoid such things.

Secondly, the monolithic kernel approach taken by Linus, while appropriate for 
an OS with a single Chief Designer, makes it much more difficult for others to 
experiment with kernel extensions.  You try to modify the scheduler, for
for example, and then find that it's wired into the pager, and so on.  The
mach / hurd paradigm makes it much easier for folks to hack in kernel
extensions and improvements.  As with any other endeavor, if you make 
experimentation easier, you increase the chances that experimentation will
occur.

-- 
-=Paul Flaherty, N9FZX | "The National Anthem has become The Whine."
->paulf@Stanford.EDU   |  -- Charles Sykes, _A Nation of Victims_

